<HEADLINE>
CABINET ANNOUNCES 2 NEW APPOINTMENTS
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  April 9 (CNA) 04/10/07  11:25:50 (By Sofia Wu)
</P>
<P>
Chen Ming-tong, a former vice chairman of the Mainland Affairs
Council (MAC) who is now a professor of National Taiwan
University's Graduate Institute of National Development, will
serve as the MAC chairman, Executive Yuan Deputy Secretary-
General Chen Mei-ling said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chen Mei-ling also announced the Executive Yuan's decision to
appoint Legislator  Chen Ching-jun  of the ruling  Democratic
Progressive Party (DPP) as vice minister of transportation and
communications.
</P>
<P>
Chen Ming-tong will succeed Joseph Wu as the country's top China
policy planner. Wu has been appointed to serve as Taiwan's top
representative to the United States.
</P>
<P>
As his transfer to new job requires the approval of National
Taiwan University, Chen Ming-tong refrained from issuing any
comment on his new assignment. He just said whether he would
accept his new job will depend on whether the school would allow
him to work for the MAC on loan.
</P>
